## Conclusion

Jean-Jacques Rousseau’s political philosophy was undeniably a cornerstone of the ideological foundation of the French Revolution. His advocacy for popular sovereignty, equality, and civic participation galvanized revolutionary leaders and the broader populace to challenge the ancien régime. Rousseau’s vision of a social contract where individuals collectively govern themselves inspired the revolutionary restructuring of French society and government.

However, the practical application of his ideas revealed inherent tensions and contradictions. While promoting liberty and equality, Rousseau’s concept of the *general will* was used to justify authoritarian measures, including the Reign of Terror. Additionally, his skepticism of large republics and ambiguous statements complicated the implementation of his theories in the complex context of late 18th-century France.

In sum, Rousseau’s influence on the French Revolution was profound and multifaceted. His ideas provided both the philosophical impetus for revolutionary change and a framework that, when interpreted in various ways, shaped the revolution’s successes and excesses. Understanding Rousseau’s role is essential for comprehending the intellectual origins and dynamics of one of history’s most transformative political upheavals.

